1
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:01,280
It's obviously a major malfunction.

2
00:01:17,595 --> 00:01:20,115
...their President is a crook.
Well, I'm not a crook.

3
00:01:23,979 --> 00:01:27,499
Robert Kennedy was shot
in that ballroom.

4
00:01:30,072 --> 00:01:32,352
Thank God Almighty,
we are free at last!

5
00:01:32,659 --> 00:01:35,339
A sniper has fired
at President Kennedy.

6
00:01:42,757 --> 00:01:46,597
Or have you ever been
a member of the Communist party?

7
00:01:50,936 --> 00:01:52,856
Hi-yo, Silver!

8
00:01:57,654 --> 00:01:59,214
... 194 1...

9
00:01:59,866 --> 00:02:02,906
...a date which will live in infamy.

10
00:02:07,126 --> 00:02:11,126
We bring you the final edition of
our Maxwell House Good News of 1939.

11
00:02:11,675 --> 00:02:14,915
Good evening, Mr. and Mrs. North
America, and all the ships at sea.

12
00:02:19,979 --> 00:02:23,979
The only thing we have to fear
is fear itself.

13
00:03:33,796 --> 00:03:34,876
CQ...

14
00:03:35,340 --> 00:03:37,260
...this is W-9 GFO.

15
00:03:39,638 --> 00:03:42,798
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here.
Come back?

16
00:03:46,940 --> 00:03:48,060
CQ...

17
00:03:48,317 --> 00:03:50,837
...this is W-9 GFO here.

18
00:03:51,822 --> 00:03:52,982
Come back?

19
00:03:56,955 --> 00:04:00,955
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.
Is anybody out there?

20
00:04:02,129 --> 00:04:03,209
Not getting anything.

21
00:04:03,548 --> 00:04:04,988
Small moves, Ellie.

22
00:04:06,761 --> 00:04:07,841
Small moves.

23
00:04:10,516 --> 00:04:14,076
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here.
Come back?

24
00:04:15,190 --> 00:04:16,790
Copy, W-9 GFO.

25
00:04:17,026 --> 00:04:18,826
K-4 WLD here.

26
00:04:19,363 --> 00:04:20,723
What do I say?

27
00:04:20,948 --> 00:04:22,388
Just be yourself.

28
00:04:22,910 --> 00:04:25,470
Where are you, K-4 WLD?
Come back?

29
00:04:25,831 --> 00:04:27,071
Pensacola.
Over.

30
00:04:27,374 --> 00:04:28,854
Pensacola, where's Pensacola?

31
00:04:29,294 --> 00:04:30,694
I'll give you a hint.

32
00:04:31,422 --> 00:04:32,502
Orange juice.

33
00:04:35,386 --> 00:04:38,906
Copy that, K-4 WLD. How's the
weather down there in Florida?

34
00:04:40,268 --> 00:04:42,148
Pensacola, Florida.

35
00:04:42,939 --> 00:04:44,739
I have to tell you, Sparks.

36
00:04:45,610 --> 00:04:47,850
1,116 miles.

37
00:04:49,449 --> 00:04:50,569
Pretty good.

38
00:04:50,951 --> 00:04:52,351
That's the farthest yet.

39
00:05:05,305 --> 00:05:07,065
Can we hear all the way to New York?

40
00:05:07,434 --> 00:05:08,554
Sure.

41
00:05:09,979 --> 00:05:11,899
Can we hear all the way
to California?

42
00:05:12,274 --> 00:05:13,914
I don't see why not.

43
00:05:14,694 --> 00:05:16,614
Can we hear all the way to Alaska?

44
00:05:17,114 --> 00:05:18,354
On a really clear day.

45
00:05:18,617 --> 00:05:20,537
Can we hear all the way to China?

46
00:05:21,663 --> 00:05:24,063
On a really, really clear day.

47
00:05:26,003 --> 00:05:28,083
Could we talk to the moon?

48
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:31,520
If it's a big enough radio,
I don't see why not.

49
00:05:32,303 --> 00:05:34,223
Could we talk to Jupiter?

50
00:05:34,515 --> 00:05:36,915
Or what's the one after that?

51
00:05:37,478 --> 00:05:38,798
Don't tell me.

52
00:05:41,192 --> 00:05:42,512
I'll give you a hint.

53
00:05:43,028 --> 00:05:44,108
Hula-Hoops.

54
00:05:44,363 --> 00:05:46,283
Saturn!
Could we talk to Saturn?

55
00:05:52,041 --> 00:05:54,441
Dad, could we talk to Mom?

56
00:06:00,220 --> 00:06:03,300
I don't think even the biggest radio
could reach that far.

57
00:06:08,440 --> 00:06:10,200
All right, no more stalling.

58
00:06:15,242 --> 00:06:16,642
Pensacola!

59
00:06:24,547 --> 00:06:25,747
That's a beauty.

60
00:06:27,259 --> 00:06:28,659
Now get some sleep.

61
00:06:37,107 --> 00:06:38,347
Hey, Dad?

62
00:06:39,444 --> 00:06:42,004
Do you think there's people
on other planets?

63
00:06:42,282 --> 00:06:43,922
I don't know, Sparks.

64
00:06:45,453 --> 00:06:47,053
But I guess I'd say...

65
00:06:47,623 --> 00:06:49,383
...if it is just us...

66
00:06:51,128 --> 00:06:53,208
...it seems like
an awful waste of space.

67
00:07:12,993 --> 00:07:15,233
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

68
00:07:15,497 --> 00:07:18,057
Repeat. This is W-9 GFO.
Come back?

69
00:07:26,180 --> 00:07:28,100
I'm going to need a bigger antenna.

70
00:07:55,222 --> 00:07:56,782
What do you think, Doc Arroway?

71
00:07:57,100 --> 00:07:58,500
Isn't she a beauty?

72
00:08:02,692 --> 00:08:03,772
It'll do.

73
00:08:04,069 --> 00:08:05,949
The village is five miles away.

74
00:08:06,405 --> 00:08:08,365
There's a general store
in the cantina.

75
00:08:08,617 --> 00:08:10,657
They can order anything
from San Juan.

76
00:08:10,912 --> 00:08:12,352
When can I get dish time?

77
00:08:12,581 --> 00:08:16,101
Dr. Clark said you couldn't wait.
Your first shift is tonight.

78
00:09:12,336 --> 00:09:13,456
Go back.

79
00:09:15,466 --> 00:09:18,106
Try back a little bit.
You had something there.

80
00:09:19,513 --> 00:09:20,473
There!

81
00:09:20,848 --> 00:09:23,928
-Right there?
-You hear it? Right there, that's it.

82
00:09:24,354 --> 00:09:27,874
All right, 1221 .46.
That's well within the L-band.

83
00:09:28,360 --> 00:09:29,320
Check off-axis.

84
00:09:30,362 --> 00:09:31,402
On it.

85
00:09:33,409 --> 00:09:34,809
It's not in the neighborhood.

86
00:09:43,715 --> 00:09:45,635
Here it is.
J-1741 ...

87
00:09:46,011 --> 00:09:47,611
... + 2748.

88
00:09:47,888 --> 00:09:50,928
Catalogued November 4, 1982.
Pulsar.

89
00:09:53,730 --> 00:09:56,730
Must've been the glitch
in the timing that threw me.

90
00:09:57,068 --> 00:09:58,668
Must've been a starquake.

91
00:10:00,073 --> 00:10:03,913
I think it's great that you listen.
Most don't do that anymore.

92
00:10:04,246 --> 00:10:06,926
It's just an old habit.
It makes it feel more real.

93
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:08,130
Ellie.

94
00:10:08,419 --> 00:10:09,539
Kent Clark.

95
00:10:12,466 --> 00:10:13,986
They said you'd been...

96
00:10:14,260 --> 00:10:16,580
...up at Owen's Valley
working under Drumlin.

97
00:10:16,889 --> 00:10:18,209
How'd you like him?

98
00:10:21,479 --> 00:10:25,439
That much? About what I'd expect
after what he had to say about you.

99
00:10:25,944 --> 00:10:27,544
And what was that?

100
00:10:28,114 --> 00:10:29,554
That you are brilliant...

101
00:10:29,909 --> 00:10:31,069
...driven...

102
00:10:31,452 --> 00:10:32,892
...a major pain in the ass...

103
00:10:33,247 --> 00:10:36,007
...and obsessed with a field
of study he considers tantamount...

104
00:10:36,293 --> 00:10:37,693
...to professional suicide.

105
00:10:38,505 --> 00:10:39,465
Anything else?

106
00:10:39,673 --> 00:10:41,393
Those were the highlights.

107
00:10:41,926 --> 00:10:44,366
David, Dr. Vernon.
Dr. Arroway.

108
00:10:45,932 --> 00:10:49,972
Believe you've already met our tireless
research assistant, Mr. Fisher...

109
00:10:50,814 --> 00:10:53,054
...as well as his cologne.

110
00:10:53,777 --> 00:10:56,057
Brook's looking at the black hole
in M-87.

111
00:10:56,322 --> 00:11:00,002
Ellie's studying Markarian 541,
a major gamma ray source.

112
00:11:00,495 --> 00:11:04,935
Dr. Arroway will be spending her
precious telescope time listening for...

113
00:11:05,878 --> 00:11:07,758
...listening for...

114
00:11:08,048 --> 00:11:09,488
Little green men.

115
00:11:17,646 --> 00:11:18,886
One down...

116
00:11:19,523 --> 00:11:21,083
...a couple billion to go.

117
00:11:37,967 --> 00:11:39,727
Arecibo, right?

118
00:11:41,013 --> 00:11:42,133
Does it show?

119
00:11:44,310 --> 00:11:45,390
Cracker Jack?

120
00:11:45,687 --> 00:11:46,407
No, thanks.

121
00:11:46,688 --> 00:11:47,928
Mind if I sit down?

122
00:11:49,901 --> 00:11:53,661
I hear the locals,
they call it "El Radar."

123
00:11:54,032 --> 00:11:56,552
Convinced it has some
dark military purpose.

124
00:11:57,079 --> 00:11:58,399
I think we're harmless.

125
00:11:59,958 --> 00:12:01,038
Palmer Joss.

126
00:12:01,919 --> 00:12:04,279
-Ellie Arroway.
-Nice to meet you, Ellie.

127
00:12:05,633 --> 00:12:08,273
What are you studying up there?

128
00:12:10,223 --> 00:12:11,543
The usual.

129
00:12:11,767 --> 00:12:15,447
Nebulae, quasars, pulsars,
stuff like that.

130
00:12:15,940 --> 00:12:17,380
What are you writing?

131
00:12:17,776 --> 00:12:19,816
The usual.
Nouns, adverbs...

132
00:12:20,154 --> 00:12:21,634
...adjective here and there.

133
00:12:23,451 --> 00:12:24,891
I work on a project, SETI.

134
00:12:25,788 --> 00:12:27,708
Search for
Extraterrestrial Intelligence?

135
00:12:29,960 --> 00:12:31,600
That is out there!

136
00:12:32,840 --> 00:12:35,080
Are you a student or something?

137
00:12:35,677 --> 00:12:37,717
I'm a writer.
I'm writing a book.

138
00:12:38,306 --> 00:12:39,586
I'm here doing research...

139
00:12:39,808 --> 00:12:42,848
...about how technology affects
Third World cultures.

140
00:12:43,146 --> 00:12:45,706
I'm also looking for this guy,
David Drumlin.

141
00:12:46,109 --> 00:12:50,029
He's head of the National Science
Foundation. I want an interview.

142
00:12:51,492 --> 00:12:53,132
I take it you know him?

143
00:12:54,705 --> 00:12:56,105
You could say that.

144
00:12:57,501 --> 00:12:58,901
SETI.

145
00:12:59,170 --> 00:13:00,770
That's fringe!

146
00:13:01,298 --> 00:13:05,538
I've crossed paths with him. Something
like that must really chap his ass.

147
00:13:08,684 --> 00:13:09,684
Compass.

148
00:13:11,730 --> 00:13:12,970
That's for you.

149
00:13:17,864 --> 00:13:19,264
You better keep this.

150
00:13:20,535 --> 00:13:22,135
Might save your life someday.

151
00:13:27,003 --> 00:13:28,523
Have dinner with me tonight?

152
00:13:31,551 --> 00:13:34,751
I don't make a good
research subject. I'm not quotable.

153
00:13:35,181 --> 00:13:37,421
No quotes.
Scout's honor.

154
00:13:37,894 --> 00:13:39,174
Good meal, good company.

155
00:13:40,064 --> 00:13:41,344
I've got to go.

156
00:13:50,537 --> 00:13:52,297
Drumlin's coming in Tuesday.

157
00:14:01,262 --> 00:14:04,462
Now I remember
why I took that desk job.

158
00:14:06,144 --> 00:14:08,064
Dr. Drumlin, how are you?

159
00:14:09,774 --> 00:14:11,214
Glad you could make it.

160
00:14:12,445 --> 00:14:15,285
If I'd known it took 3 planes,
I might've reconsidered.

161
00:14:15,616 --> 00:14:16,896
How is that new office?

162
00:14:17,160 --> 00:14:21,680
Still settling in. They already want to
give half my budget to the Pentagon.

163
00:14:22,626 --> 00:14:24,866
Still waiting for E.T. to call?

164
00:14:26,966 --> 00:14:28,566
Good to see you too!

165
00:14:29,136 --> 00:14:30,096
Asshole!

166
00:14:30,429 --> 00:14:32,509
Looks like it's
going to be a long night.

167
00:14:32,850 --> 00:14:37,290
Science must be accountable to the
people paying for it, the taxpayers.

168
00:14:37,648 --> 00:14:40,848
We must stop wasting money
on pie-in-the-sky abstractions...

169
00:14:41,154 --> 00:14:43,874
...and spend it on practical,
measurable ways...

170
00:14:44,158 --> 00:14:46,758
...to improve the lives
of the people who are paying.

171
00:14:47,037 --> 00:14:50,077
Not unlike my L-band,
globular clusters work.

172
00:14:50,459 --> 00:14:53,299
You want to do away
with all pure research now?

173
00:14:53,630 --> 00:14:56,870
What's wrong with science
being practical? Even profitable?

174
00:14:57,219 --> 00:14:59,259
Nothing, as long as your motive...

175
00:14:59,639 --> 00:15:03,359
...is the search for truth. Which is
what the pursuit of science is.

176
00:15:06,149 --> 00:15:08,429
That's an interesting position
from a man...

177
00:15:08,736 --> 00:15:11,256
...on a crusade against
the evils of technology...

178
00:15:11,657 --> 00:15:12,777
...Father Joss.

179
00:15:13,493 --> 00:15:16,693
I'm not against technology, Doctor.
I'm against...

180
00:15:17,040 --> 00:15:20,120
...the men who deify it
at the expense of human truth.

181
00:15:24,342 --> 00:15:27,582
Kent, I need to have
a word with you. Over here, please.

182
00:15:33,397 --> 00:15:36,397
You think that hurt my chances
with that interview?

183
00:15:37,153 --> 00:15:38,513
You're a priest?

184
00:15:40,491 --> 00:15:41,611
Not really.

185
00:15:42,411 --> 00:15:45,051
I got my Masters in Divinity...

186
00:15:45,665 --> 00:15:48,945
...then left the seminary to do
secular humanitarian work...

187
00:15:49,337 --> 00:15:51,657
...coordinating
Third World churches.

188
00:15:52,509 --> 00:15:54,509
I couldn't live
with the celibacy thing.

189
00:15:59,185 --> 00:16:01,185
You could call me
a man of the cloth...

190
00:16:02,523 --> 00:16:04,043
...without the cloth.

191
00:16:07,447 --> 00:16:09,007
You want to get out of here?

192
00:16:11,078 --> 00:16:15,718
You see that large W-shaped
constellation there? That's Cassiopeia.

193
00:16:16,294 --> 00:16:20,534
And Cassiopeia A gives off
a whole lot of radio signals.

194
00:16:21,092 --> 00:16:22,652
I listen to them a lot.

195
00:16:23,012 --> 00:16:25,212
It's a remnant of a supernova.

196
00:16:26,267 --> 00:16:28,827
When did you know
you wanted to be an astronomer?

197
00:16:31,274 --> 00:16:33,434
When I was about eight years old...

198
00:16:33,820 --> 00:16:35,420
...watching the sunset...

199
00:16:36,532 --> 00:16:38,572
...I asked Dad, "What's that bright
star over there?"

200
00:16:42,165 --> 00:16:45,125
He said that it wasn't a star.
It was...

201
00:16:47,173 --> 00:16:49,493
...a whole planet called Venus...

202
00:16:53,181 --> 00:16:56,301
...which should be over there soon.

203
00:16:57,438 --> 00:16:59,718
He said,
"You know why they called it Venus?

204
00:17:00,275 --> 00:17:03,395
Because they thought
it was so beautiful and glowing.

205
00:17:03,780 --> 00:17:05,300
But they didn't know...

206
00:17:06,075 --> 00:17:08,555
...that it's filled with...

207
00:17:09,873 --> 00:17:13,153
...deadly gases
and sulfuric acid rain."

208
00:17:14,630 --> 00:17:18,030
Wow, I thought,
"This is it! I'm hooked!"

209
00:17:20,388 --> 00:17:23,948
There are four hundred billion
stars out there...

210
00:17:24,311 --> 00:17:26,111
...just in our galaxy alone.

211
00:17:27,190 --> 00:17:30,670
If only one out of a million
of those had planets...

212
00:17:31,237 --> 00:17:34,197
...if just one out of a million
of those had life...

213
00:17:34,534 --> 00:17:38,534
...and if just one out of a million
of those had intelligent life...

214
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:43,860
...there would be literally millions
of civilizations out there.

215
00:17:45,926 --> 00:17:47,446
If there wasn't...

216
00:17:48,429 --> 00:17:50,509
...it'd be an awful waste of space.

217
00:17:56,525 --> 00:17:57,645
Amen.

218
00:18:06,623 --> 00:18:10,463
So I was lying there,
just looking at the sky.

219
00:18:14,551 --> 00:18:17,431
And then I felt something.
I don't know.

220
00:18:18,891 --> 00:18:21,451
All I know is that I wasn't alone.

221
00:18:21,937 --> 00:18:26,017
For the first time in my life
I wasn't scared of nothing...

222
00:18:27,111 --> 00:18:28,631
...not even dying.

223
00:18:34,330 --> 00:18:36,130
It was God.

224
00:18:38,837 --> 00:18:40,757
And there's no chance that...

225
00:18:41,341 --> 00:18:45,421
...you had this experience because
some part of you needed to have it?

226
00:18:46,849 --> 00:18:50,209
I'm a reasonably intelligent guy,
but this...

227
00:18:53,233 --> 00:18:56,713
My intellect
couldn't even touch this.

228
00:18:57,364 --> 00:18:58,324
No.

229
00:19:00,870 --> 00:19:03,350
I've been to Sunday school
a few times.

230
00:19:05,710 --> 00:19:06,550
And?

231
00:19:06,795 --> 00:19:11,155
I kept asking all these
really annoying questions like...

232
00:19:12,261 --> 00:19:14,621
..."Where did Mrs. Cain come from?"

233
00:19:16,643 --> 00:19:18,843
And pretty soon they asked my dad...

234
00:19:19,188 --> 00:19:21,788
...if he wouldn't mind
keeping me home from now on.

235
00:19:22,193 --> 00:19:23,433
Your dad...

236
00:19:25,197 --> 00:19:26,677
Is it this guy?

237
00:19:26,908 --> 00:19:28,068
Yeah.

238
00:19:30,288 --> 00:19:32,208
You're close to him, aren't you?

239
00:19:33,584 --> 00:19:36,544
I was. He died
when I was nine years old.

240
00:19:38,926 --> 00:19:40,846
I never got to know my mother.

241
00:19:42,514 --> 00:19:43,794
I'm sorry.

242
00:19:48,398 --> 00:19:50,238
That's got to be tough.

243
00:19:54,782 --> 00:19:56,382
Being alone.

244
00:20:05,339 --> 00:20:06,499
What do you say...

245
00:20:06,758 --> 00:20:10,158
...we pack a picnic tomorrow
and hike up to Mount Arecibo?

246
00:20:11,140 --> 00:20:14,020
I don't think I can.
I've got to work.

247
00:20:15,938 --> 00:20:19,218
How about dinner tomorrow night?
I know a great dive.

248
00:20:19,736 --> 00:20:21,296
No, I don't think so.

249
00:20:25,995 --> 00:20:28,035
Ellie, did I miss something?

250
00:20:30,335 --> 00:20:31,415
No.

251
00:20:31,670 --> 00:20:33,430
Shit, I'm late!

252
00:20:34,507 --> 00:20:37,267
I told Kent
that I'd be there at 10:30.

253
00:20:40,016 --> 00:20:41,736
I'm not trying to push you.

254
00:20:42,019 --> 00:20:44,219
I've wanted to look at
this sector for weeks.

255
00:20:44,522 --> 00:20:46,122
Just hang out...

256
00:20:46,525 --> 00:20:49,405
...and sleep in.
There's food in the fridge.

257
00:20:51,199 --> 00:20:52,279
How can I reach you?

258
00:20:53,869 --> 00:20:56,109
Just leave your number.
I'll call you.

259
00:21:17,946 --> 00:21:18,866
Dad!

260
00:21:20,951 --> 00:21:23,471
It's starting,
you're going to miss it!

261
00:21:27,085 --> 00:21:29,205
Dad, there's another one!
Hurry up!

262
00:21:29,547 --> 00:21:31,747
In a minute, Sparks!
I'm almost done.

263
00:21:32,092 --> 00:21:34,492
There's another one.
Come on, hurry up, Dad!

264
00:22:30,261 --> 00:22:31,421
I'll get the medicine.

265
00:23:51,214 --> 00:23:53,854
I know it's hard
to understand this now...

266
00:23:54,886 --> 00:23:59,206
...but we aren't always meant to know
why things happen the way they do.

267
00:23:59,935 --> 00:24:02,135
Sometimes,
we just have to accept it...

268
00:24:02,439 --> 00:24:04,199
...as God's will.

269
00:24:06,236 --> 00:24:09,276
I should have kept medicine
in the downstairs bathroom.

270
00:24:10,075 --> 00:24:12,235
Then I could've gotten to it sooner.

271
00:24:38,158 --> 00:24:39,438
CQ...

272
00:24:40,703 --> 00:24:43,623
...this is W-9 GFO.
Do you copy?

273
00:24:47,296 --> 00:24:49,496
Dad, this is Ellie.
Come back.

274
00:24:52,972 --> 00:24:54,852
This is Eleanor Arroway...

275
00:24:55,183 --> 00:24:58,063
...transmitting on 14.2 megahertz.

276
00:25:04,906 --> 00:25:06,346
Are you there?

277
00:25:08,536 --> 00:25:09,896
Come back.

278
00:25:16,757 --> 00:25:18,077
Are you there?

279
00:25:19,219 --> 00:25:21,019
Dad, this is Ellie.

280
00:25:53,686 --> 00:25:56,446
Hi, Kent.
What are you doing up so early?

281
00:25:57,775 --> 00:25:59,015
I was thinking...

282
00:25:59,987 --> 00:26:01,907
...we'd make a pretty good team.

283
00:26:02,616 --> 00:26:06,016
We could put together
an ad hoc SETI program.

284
00:26:06,371 --> 00:26:08,611
You know the Very Large Array
in New Mexico?

285
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,120
It's a dynamite place
to do SETI work...

286
00:26:11,462 --> 00:26:13,142
What are you talking about?

287
00:26:15,677 --> 00:26:17,357
Drumlin pulled the plug.

288
00:26:18,180 --> 00:26:19,140
We're homeless.

289
00:26:33,495 --> 00:26:35,055
It's true, you pulled the plug?

290
00:26:35,331 --> 00:26:37,811
You can't see it now,
but I'm doing you a favor.

291
00:26:38,085 --> 00:26:41,925
You're too promising a scientist to
waste your gifts on this nonsense.

292
00:26:42,299 --> 00:26:44,219
I don't consider what could be...

293
00:26:44,511 --> 00:26:47,231
...the most important
human discovery nonsense!

294
00:26:47,682 --> 00:26:49,002
400 billion stars...

295
00:26:49,226 --> 00:26:52,026
And two probabilities.
One, there's intelligent life...

296
00:26:52,356 --> 00:26:54,756
...but too far away
to contact in your lifetime.

297
00:26:55,527 --> 00:26:57,367
-And two!
-You're making a decision...

298
00:26:57,947 --> 00:27:00,867
There's nothing but gases
and carbon compounds...

299
00:27:01,202 --> 00:27:02,202
...and you're wasting your time!

300
00:27:02,537 --> 00:27:05,377
In the meantime,
you won't be taken seriously.

301
00:27:05,709 --> 00:27:07,309
Your career will be over!

302
00:27:07,586 --> 00:27:08,706
So what?

303
00:27:09,089 --> 00:27:10,489
It's my life!

304
00:27:48,230 --> 00:27:50,630
Hey, Kent.
You were right.

305
00:27:51,151 --> 00:27:54,671
Screw Drumlin. We'll raise the money
ourselves. We'll go to New Mexico.

306
00:27:55,157 --> 00:27:57,317
Chicago's set.
Let me know how it goes.

307
00:27:57,618 --> 00:28:00,418
I've got more corporate stops
on the East Coast for you.

308
00:28:00,748 --> 00:28:03,748
Did that investor from Houston
ever get back to us?

309
00:28:04,128 --> 00:28:06,048
I'll hit him up on my way to L.A.

310
00:28:06,298 --> 00:28:08,338
Beg for some of that
Hollywood money!

311
00:28:08,635 --> 00:28:11,595
They've been making
money off aliens for years.

312
00:28:12,349 --> 00:28:14,949
-Begging is good for the soul.
-We'll see.

313
00:28:15,353 --> 00:28:16,993
Just do me a favor.

314
00:28:17,356 --> 00:28:19,756
Try not to be too...confrontational.

315
00:28:20,319 --> 00:28:22,559
Confrontational? Me?
What do you mean?

316
00:28:22,864 --> 00:28:24,464
I'll see if I left anything.

317
00:28:57,832 --> 00:29:01,472
It's a unique time in our history,
in the history of any civilization.

318
00:29:01,838 --> 00:29:04,478
It's the moment
of the acquisition of technology.

319
00:29:04,801 --> 00:29:07,561
That's the moment
where contact becomes possible.

320
00:29:08,431 --> 00:29:10,671
The Very Large Array
in New Mexico...

321
00:29:10,935 --> 00:29:13,135
...is the key to our chances
for success.

322
00:29:13,397 --> 00:29:15,437
With its 27
linked radio telescopes...

323
00:29:15,734 --> 00:29:19,134
...we can search more accurately
than at any other facility.

324
00:29:19,489 --> 00:29:24,009
We've gotten approval to buy the
telescope time from the government.

325
00:29:25,081 --> 00:29:27,201
Now all we really need is the money.

326
00:29:27,960 --> 00:29:29,880
A nice presentation, Doctor.

327
00:29:30,672 --> 00:29:33,552
But while our foundation arm
has a mandate to support...

328
00:29:33,885 --> 00:29:36,885
...experimental programs,
your proposal...

329
00:29:37,265 --> 00:29:41,105
...seems less like science,
and more like science fiction.

330
00:29:43,733 --> 00:29:45,133
Science fiction.

331
00:29:48,615 --> 00:29:49,935
You're right.

332
00:29:50,827 --> 00:29:52,147
It's crazy.

333
00:29:53,289 --> 00:29:55,729
In fact, it's even worse
than that: nuts!

334
00:29:57,921 --> 00:29:59,321
Want to hear something nutty?

335
00:29:59,590 --> 00:30:02,030
Two guys wanted to build
a thing called an airplane.

336
00:30:02,344 --> 00:30:05,264
People go in it and fly like birds.
Ridiculous, right?

337
00:30:05,599 --> 00:30:07,319
What about breaking
the sound barrier...

338
00:30:07,602 --> 00:30:11,202
...or rockets to the moon, or atomic
energy or a mission to Mars?

339
00:30:11,524 --> 00:30:13,164
Science fiction, right?

340
00:30:14,946 --> 00:30:18,986
All I'm asking is for you to
just have the tiniest bit of vision.

341
00:30:19,452 --> 00:30:22,652
To step back
and look at the big picture.

342
00:30:23,208 --> 00:30:28,048
Take a chance on something which could
end up the most impactful moment...

343
00:30:28,466 --> 00:30:30,706
...for humanity, for the history...

344
00:30:31,387 --> 00:30:32,667
...of history.

345
00:30:36,478 --> 00:30:37,438
I'm sorry.

346
00:30:38,564 --> 00:30:40,164
I just spent 13 months...

347
00:30:40,817 --> 00:30:43,537
...coming into rooms
and talking to people like you.

348
00:30:44,573 --> 00:30:45,853
You're my last chance.

349
00:30:47,410 --> 00:30:48,890
Sorry I wasted your time.

350
00:30:49,205 --> 00:30:49,725
Doctor.

351
00:30:50,623 --> 00:30:51,663
Yes, sir.

352
00:31:04,102 --> 00:31:05,302
You have your money.

353
00:31:08,400 --> 00:31:09,480
Thank you.

354
00:31:11,613 --> 00:31:12,573
Thank you.

355
00:32:00,643 --> 00:32:03,523
Perfect cast!
Come on, fishy!

356
00:32:03,898 --> 00:32:05,378
Frank, look at the size...

357
00:32:05,609 --> 00:32:07,529
...of that son of a bitch!

358
00:32:20,047 --> 00:32:21,927
Welcome back, Dr. C.

359
00:32:22,258 --> 00:32:23,698
How'd it go?

360
00:32:24,470 --> 00:32:25,950
How was the trip?

361
00:32:26,222 --> 00:32:27,662
I've had better.

362
00:32:28,351 --> 00:32:31,271
Drumlin!
Is this a personal vendetta now?

363
00:32:31,605 --> 00:32:35,325
There's been enormous pressure
from other scientists as well.

364
00:32:35,653 --> 00:32:38,653
It doesn't matter. Hadden's funding
us for 2 more years.

365
00:32:38,991 --> 00:32:43,351
The government doesn't want their
telescopes used by the high priestess...

366
00:32:43,707 --> 00:32:45,627
...of the desert anymore.

367
00:32:47,045 --> 00:32:47,965
What?

368
00:32:48,171 --> 00:32:51,411
Staring at TV static for hours,
listening to washing machines.

369
00:32:51,760 --> 00:32:53,680
These stories get out!

370
00:32:53,972 --> 00:32:55,532
I was seeking patterns in the chaos!

371
00:32:55,808 --> 00:32:57,848
It doesn't matter,
we're a joke to them.

372
00:32:58,103 --> 00:32:59,423
They want us out!

373
00:33:01,274 --> 00:33:04,034
We've got 3 months
till the paperwork goes through.

374
00:33:07,992 --> 00:33:10,072
I'll start looking for
other funding.

375
00:33:10,705 --> 00:33:14,345
Could you face reality?
Just this once? We lost.

376
00:33:15,170 --> 00:33:16,490
It's over.

377
00:33:23,181 --> 00:33:24,301
Fine.

378
00:33:25,017 --> 00:33:26,577
I'm not stopping.

379
00:33:27,187 --> 00:33:30,187
If I have to, I'll go it alone.
I've done it before.

380
00:34:20,015 --> 00:34:23,575
My guest tonight is author
and theologian Palmer Joss.

381
00:34:24,313 --> 00:34:27,073
He's become a spiritual counselor...

382
00:34:27,359 --> 00:34:28,719
...and a recent fixture
at the White House.

383
00:34:29,070 --> 00:34:31,950
"God's Diplomat, "
according to The New York Times.

384
00:34:32,241 --> 00:34:35,761
His latest book, "Losing Faith, "
is currently number one...

385
00:34:36,122 --> 00:34:38,322
...on that publication's
bestseller list.

386
00:34:38,668 --> 00:34:41,508
Thanks for being here.
You've had quite a ride...

387
00:34:41,797 --> 00:34:43,197
...the last few years.

388
00:34:43,466 --> 00:34:45,066
Yeah, I sure have, Larry.

389
00:34:45,928 --> 00:34:48,048
Fish, I was thinking.

390
00:34:48,641 --> 00:34:52,761
Who would make the best astronomers?
Think about it.

391
00:34:53,272 --> 00:34:57,912
Who has the perfect synthesis
of career and lifestyle?

392
00:34:59,281 --> 00:35:00,201
I give.

393
00:35:00,450 --> 00:35:01,930
Vampires!

394
00:35:02,327 --> 00:35:04,767
Are you anti-technology
and anti-science?

395
00:35:05,123 --> 00:35:06,723
No, not at all.

396
00:35:07,126 --> 00:35:09,846
The question that
I'm asking is this:

397
00:35:10,673 --> 00:35:12,073
Are we happier...

398
00:35:12,801 --> 00:35:16,161
...as a human race? Is the world
fundamentally a better place...

399
00:35:16,473 --> 00:35:18,393
...because of science
and technology?

400
00:35:19,144 --> 00:35:21,544
We shop at home,
we surf the Web...

401
00:35:21,814 --> 00:35:24,374
...but at the same time
we feel emptier...

402
00:35:25,862 --> 00:35:27,582
...and more
cut off from each other...

403
00:35:27,823 --> 00:35:29,543
...than at any other time
in human history.

404
00:35:29,826 --> 00:35:32,266
We're becoming
a synthesized society...

405
00:35:32,706 --> 00:35:34,746
...in a hurry to get to the...

406
00:35:49,522 --> 00:35:51,162
We're looking for the meaning.

407
00:35:51,525 --> 00:35:52,805
What is the meaning?

408
00:35:53,027 --> 00:35:55,667
We have mindless jobs,
take frantic vacations.

409
00:35:56,198 --> 00:35:59,078
Deficit finance trips
to the mall to buy things...

410
00:35:59,370 --> 00:36:02,810
...that we think will fill
these holes in our lives.

411
00:36:03,376 --> 00:36:05,776
Any wonder we've lost
our sense of direction?

412
00:36:46,731 --> 00:36:48,291
Holy shit!

413
00:37:06,677 --> 00:37:07,597
Right ascension...

414
00:37:07,887 --> 00:37:11,607
...18 hours, 36 minutes,
56.2 seconds!

415
00:37:12,895 --> 00:37:14,455
Declination...

416
00:37:14,856 --> 00:37:17,736
... + 36 degrees, 46 minutes...

417
00:37:18,194 --> 00:37:20,274
...56.2 seconds!

418
00:37:22,910 --> 00:37:24,270
Confirm!

419
00:37:24,537 --> 00:37:27,537
Right ascension,
18 hours, 36 minutes...

420
00:37:27,875 --> 00:37:29,915
...56.2 seconds!

421
00:37:30,629 --> 00:37:33,389
Is anybody awake in there?
I'm moving the array!

422
00:37:33,675 --> 00:37:35,595
Confirm!

423
00:37:35,929 --> 00:37:37,289
Boss has a bogey!

424
00:37:37,556 --> 00:37:39,796
Right ascension, 18 hours...

425
00:37:44,233 --> 00:37:45,433
We're on it!

426
00:37:45,693 --> 00:37:46,653
36 hours...

427
00:37:47,070 --> 00:37:48,950
...47 minutes and 1 second!

428
00:37:49,532 --> 00:37:50,812
Strong possible...

429
00:37:51,034 --> 00:37:53,434
...pulse chain on sub-array four!

430
00:37:53,747 --> 00:37:56,187
I'm moving the rest.
Confirm coordinates!

431
00:37:57,252 --> 00:37:59,012
Check the status of the array.

432
00:37:59,380 --> 00:38:00,700
She's doing all the dishes.

433
00:38:01,216 --> 00:38:02,056
Systems nominal.

434
00:38:07,976 --> 00:38:09,056
Hello.

435
00:38:10,313 --> 00:38:11,353
Full systems check!

436
00:38:12,232 --> 00:38:14,872
Coordinates confirmed.
Willie's checking the system.

437
00:38:15,237 --> 00:38:17,957
Stay on top of
the systems diagnostics!

438
00:38:18,366 --> 00:38:20,006
Check reference point offsets.

439
00:38:20,286 --> 00:38:24,126
And I want you off-axis
on 27 the second we get there!

440
00:38:24,459 --> 00:38:26,899
And tell Willie
to break out the big boy!

441
00:38:28,590 --> 00:38:29,590
Copy that.

442
00:38:31,093 --> 00:38:32,333
Yeah! Go, Ellie!

443
00:38:32,596 --> 00:38:35,636
I hear it on the headphones.
We got to be sure about this.

444
00:38:36,101 --> 00:38:38,181
Give me another array status.

445
00:38:40,107 --> 00:38:43,467
Her four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

446
00:38:46,115 --> 00:38:48,355
But there's a bad drive on 16.

447
00:38:48,661 --> 00:38:51,021
The four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

448
00:38:51,373 --> 00:38:54,053
There's a bad drive on 16.
Copy that?

449
00:38:55,629 --> 00:38:57,549
What shall I do
about the source queue?

450
00:38:57,841 --> 00:38:59,721
Forget it and hold the queue.

451
00:39:00,136 --> 00:39:04,136
Get ready to set the target frequency
to manual the second we're aligned.

452
00:39:04,518 --> 00:39:08,758
Do you copy? I want you to go
off-axis on 27 the second we're there!

453
00:39:09,149 --> 00:39:11,709
And leave the LO frequency
where it is!

454
00:39:12,154 --> 00:39:15,154
Don't let it get away!
If you lose it, scan the band!

455
00:39:15,492 --> 00:39:18,052
Run every frequency
you can think of.

456
00:39:23,504 --> 00:39:24,784
How you doing?

457
00:39:29,387 --> 00:39:30,467
Talk to me, guys.

458
00:39:30,723 --> 00:39:34,243
Partially polarized moving pulses,
amplitude modulated.

459
00:39:34,604 --> 00:39:38,124
We're locked. Systems are fine.
What's the frequency?

460
00:39:38,526 --> 00:39:39,486
4.46...

461
00:39:39,736 --> 00:39:41,176
...23 gigahertz.

462
00:39:43,074 --> 00:39:44,634
Hydrogen times pi.

463
00:39:45,077 --> 00:39:46,157
Told you!

464
00:39:46,454 --> 00:39:48,094
Strong sucker too!

465
00:39:49,208 --> 00:39:50,688
I got it!
I'm patched in!

466
00:39:51,462 --> 00:39:52,502
Let me hear.

467
00:39:58,222 --> 00:39:59,542
Listen to that.

468
00:40:01,894 --> 00:40:03,774
Make me a liar, Fish.

469
00:40:04,314 --> 00:40:06,994
It could be AWACS
out of Kirkland jamming us.

470
00:40:07,277 --> 00:40:08,397
But I doubt it.

471
00:40:08,695 --> 00:40:10,775
See if F.U.D.D.'s reading it too.

472
00:40:12,952 --> 00:40:14,992
Patch it back
and give me the off-axis.

473
00:40:15,664 --> 00:40:17,264
-We recording?
-Never stopped.

474
00:40:19,420 --> 00:40:20,660
Thank you, Elmer!

475
00:40:20,922 --> 00:40:22,682
AWACS status is negative.

476
00:40:22,925 --> 00:40:23,885
White Sands?

477
00:40:24,177 --> 00:40:25,697
On this frequency? No.

478
00:40:26,263 --> 00:40:27,503
I'll punch up the darks.

479
00:40:30,770 --> 00:40:31,890
How's spying tonight?

480
00:40:33,065 --> 00:40:34,305
Come on!

481
00:40:36,695 --> 00:40:39,055
NORAD's not tracking
any snoops in this vector.

482
00:40:39,574 --> 00:40:40,894
Shuttle's in sleep mode.

483
00:40:41,285 --> 00:40:43,365
Okay, point source confirmed.

484
00:40:43,747 --> 00:40:45,267
Whatever it is, it ain't local.

485
00:40:45,541 --> 00:40:46,341
Position?

486
00:40:46,585 --> 00:40:48,985
I checked interferometry.
Somewhere in Lyra.

487
00:40:49,297 --> 00:40:50,857
-Vega?
-Can't be!

488
00:40:51,175 --> 00:40:53,095
It's only 26 light years away.

489
00:40:53,386 --> 00:40:55,226
-Peak intensity?
-Coming up!

490
00:40:56,599 --> 00:40:57,279
Vega.

491
00:40:58,102 --> 00:41:01,822
Vega. I scanned it a bunch of times
at Arecibo. It was always negative.

492
00:41:02,191 --> 00:41:03,111
Got it!

493
00:41:03,318 --> 00:41:05,118
Reading over 100 janskys.

494
00:41:05,905 --> 00:41:08,305
Jesus! I can pick it up on my...

495
00:41:11,329 --> 00:41:12,289
No!

496
00:41:45,630 --> 00:41:46,590
Come on!

497
00:41:48,885 --> 00:41:50,005
It's restarting.

498
00:41:51,514 --> 00:41:53,194
Wait a minute.
Those are numbers.

499
00:41:53,433 --> 00:41:55,153
That was 3, before it was 2.

500
00:41:56,688 --> 00:41:59,168
Base 10 numbers.
Count and see how far we get.

501
00:42:00,360 --> 00:42:00,880
One.

502
00:42:07,579 --> 00:42:08,539
Seven.

503
00:42:11,418 --> 00:42:12,898
Those are primes.

504
00:42:13,212 --> 00:42:16,252
2, 3, 5, 7 are all prime numbers.

505
00:42:16,842 --> 00:42:18,642
No way that's a natural phenomenon!

506
00:42:18,929 --> 00:42:21,649
Let's just calm down
and pull up the star file on Vega.

507
00:42:23,269 --> 00:42:26,429
It doesn't make any sense.
The system is too young.

508
00:42:26,774 --> 00:42:28,374
It can't have a planetary system...

509
00:42:28,610 --> 00:42:31,730
...let alone life
or a technological civilization.

510
00:42:32,115 --> 00:42:34,475
Maybe they're not from there,
they're visiting.

511
00:42:34,786 --> 00:42:37,986
Spacecraft? This system's full
of debris. It'd get clobbered.

512
00:42:38,541 --> 00:42:42,461
Not if they used their
laser blasters and photon torpedoes.

513
00:42:42,881 --> 00:42:45,681
-That's not funny.
-How else can we explain it!

514
00:42:46,344 --> 00:42:49,184
He's right. If we go public
with this and we're wrong...

515
00:42:49,474 --> 00:42:51,634
...it's over. We're cooked.

516
00:42:54,565 --> 00:42:55,885
I wish Kent was here.

517
00:42:56,150 --> 00:42:59,430
Whatever it is, let's do something.
Vega will set.

518
00:43:02,994 --> 00:43:07,154
Position confirmed. We've got 4.4623
gigahertz, confirmed.

519
00:43:07,500 --> 00:43:10,260
We've got 112 janskys.

520
00:43:10,672 --> 00:43:12,792
Do you have a source location yet?

521
00:43:15,471 --> 00:43:17,751
We put it right smack in the middle.

522
00:43:18,517 --> 00:43:19,717
Vega.

523
00:43:21,938 --> 00:43:24,738
Thanks. Keep tracking
and we'll get back to you.

524
00:43:25,110 --> 00:43:26,350
Right-o.

525
00:43:37,712 --> 00:43:39,392
101 . The pulse sequenced...

526
00:43:39,631 --> 00:43:42,911
...through every prime number
between 2 and 101 .

527
00:43:44,972 --> 00:43:46,572
Who do we call now?

528
00:43:49,896 --> 00:43:50,856
Everybody.

529
00:43:58,659 --> 00:44:02,059
The rumors are flying,
the implications extraordinary.

530
00:44:02,415 --> 00:44:04,175
Detection of an unidentified...

531
00:44:04,501 --> 00:44:08,541
...radio source from space
can neither be confirmed nor denied.

532
00:44:08,966 --> 00:44:10,766
But the military arriving...

533
00:44:11,052 --> 00:44:14,492
Sources close to the VLA
report they have been contacted...

534
00:44:14,850 --> 00:44:16,770
...by some form
of intelligent being...

535
00:44:17,061 --> 00:44:21,421
...living outside our solar system.
Again, there is no confirmation.

536
00:44:24,739 --> 00:44:26,739
I want all of these people
out of here.

537
00:44:27,660 --> 00:44:28,940
Where's the girl?

538
00:44:33,627 --> 00:44:34,907
22 stations worldwide...

539
00:44:35,171 --> 00:44:36,531
...now confirm the signal.

540
00:44:36,757 --> 00:44:38,357
Vega's now below our horizon.

541
00:44:38,635 --> 00:44:40,875
You're hearing the signal
from the Russian...

542
00:44:41,180 --> 00:44:42,740
Get decryption people here.

543
00:44:43,016 --> 00:44:44,976
Lunacharsky's visiting at Cal Tech.

544
00:44:45,269 --> 00:44:46,589
Explain this to me.

545
00:44:46,855 --> 00:44:50,735
If the source of the signal is so
sophisticated...why the remedial math?

546
00:44:51,111 --> 00:44:52,471
Why not just speak English?

547
00:44:52,697 --> 00:44:55,977
Maybe because 70%%% of the planet
speaks other languages.

548
00:44:56,286 --> 00:44:59,006
Mathematics is the
only truly universal language.

549
00:44:59,791 --> 00:45:02,231
It's no coincidence
that they're using primes.

550
00:45:02,587 --> 00:45:03,467
I don't get it.

551
00:45:03,797 --> 00:45:04,957
Prime numbers.

552
00:45:05,216 --> 00:45:08,576
Integers only divisible
by themselves and 1 .

553
00:45:11,683 --> 00:45:14,403
We think this may be a beacon,
an announcement...

554
00:45:14,813 --> 00:45:16,493
...to get our attention.

555
00:45:16,732 --> 00:45:20,332
If it's attention you want,
you got that. One thing: Vega.

556
00:45:20,697 --> 00:45:24,017
People have looked at Vega
for years, with no results.

557
00:45:24,327 --> 00:45:27,167
Yesterday they start
broadcasting primes. Why?

558
00:45:27,540 --> 00:45:28,820
It's hardly yesterday.

559
00:45:29,084 --> 00:45:31,604
The signal's been transmitting
for 26 years.

560
00:45:33,006 --> 00:45:34,446
Excuse me, who are you?

561
00:45:34,717 --> 00:45:37,037
Michael Kitz,
National Security Advisor.

562
00:45:37,346 --> 00:45:38,626
Your reputation...

563
00:45:38,848 --> 00:45:42,128
First, ask the gentlemen
with the guns to wait outside.

564
00:45:42,938 --> 00:45:44,938
This is a civilian facility.

565
00:45:51,575 --> 00:45:52,935
With all due respect...

566
00:45:53,203 --> 00:45:54,043
Excuse me.

567
00:45:55,581 --> 00:45:57,701
Hi! I'm so glad you're back!

568
00:45:58,377 --> 00:45:59,537
Come hear this.

569
00:46:00,297 --> 00:46:01,577
Is this great?

570
00:46:01,799 --> 00:46:04,079
-Who are all these people?
-I have no idea.

571
00:46:04,386 --> 00:46:07,426
Sit down. We need help
with the spectrum analysis.

572
00:46:07,766 --> 00:46:09,286
-I'll get on it.
-Headsets.

573
00:46:09,602 --> 00:46:11,682
I'll just come right to the point.

574
00:46:11,981 --> 00:46:15,821
Announcing this all over the world may
well be a breach of national security.

575
00:46:16,153 --> 00:46:17,793
It's not a person-to-person call.

576
00:46:18,073 --> 00:46:22,033
You think a civilization sending this
message intends it just for Americans?

577
00:46:22,413 --> 00:46:24,173
You might have consulted us.

578
00:46:24,624 --> 00:46:28,464
-The contents could be very sensitive.
-You want to classify prime numbers?

579
00:46:29,256 --> 00:46:32,456
Due to earth's rotation, we're
in line with Vega only hours a day.

580
00:46:32,803 --> 00:46:36,963
The only way to monitor the signal
is to cooperate with other stations.

581
00:46:37,351 --> 00:46:41,511
If Dr. Arroway hadn't acted quickly,
we'd have lost key elements.

582
00:46:41,858 --> 00:46:43,338
Fine, they've got the primes.

583
00:46:43,652 --> 00:46:46,292
But if a more significant
transmission is to come...

584
00:46:46,657 --> 00:46:48,537
We need help to receive and decode.

585
00:46:48,826 --> 00:46:51,346
You understand
that my job is to protect...

586
00:46:52,749 --> 00:46:54,589
-Listen.
-I hear it.

587
00:46:54,961 --> 00:46:55,881
Hear what?

588
00:46:56,129 --> 00:46:57,049
Harmonic.

589
00:46:57,297 --> 00:47:00,977
Bingo! I had Willie ask Rattan
to retune to 8.9247 gigahertz.

590
00:47:01,303 --> 00:47:02,863
There's a lot more here.

591
00:47:03,139 --> 00:47:05,699
-Get on the negative sideband.
-I'm already on it.

592
00:47:05,977 --> 00:47:07,057
What is it?

593
00:47:07,312 --> 00:47:08,752
Another signal!

594
00:47:08,981 --> 00:47:11,741
A second signal at double
the frequency. Looks like...

595
00:47:12,695 --> 00:47:13,975
Get a TV monitor!

596
00:47:14,781 --> 00:47:16,581
Patch it into the image processor.

597
00:47:16,868 --> 00:47:18,068
Want the new data?

598
00:47:18,328 --> 00:47:20,048
Yeah, the new one we just recorded.

599
00:47:20,331 --> 00:47:22,211
David, explain this to me, please.

600
00:47:22,501 --> 00:47:25,181
There's another signal.
Looks like a TV transmission.

601
00:47:25,506 --> 00:47:26,426
We're hot.

602
00:47:26,716 --> 00:47:29,316
Go get the blinds.
There is a lot of glare.

603
00:47:30,513 --> 00:47:31,873
You're patched in.

604
00:47:32,182 --> 00:47:35,462
It's definitely an image.
Let's try and stabilize it.

605
00:47:40,361 --> 00:47:42,001
What do you make of that?

606
00:47:42,280 --> 00:47:45,160
It's two different
interlaced frames. I'm framing one.

607
00:47:48,623 --> 00:47:51,263
-lt's just noise.
-Trying frame two.

608
00:47:52,587 --> 00:47:55,787
I've got an offset carrier.
I think it's audio.

609
00:47:56,134 --> 00:47:57,334
Plug it in!

610
00:48:01,726 --> 00:48:02,926
Center that segment.

611
00:48:03,186 --> 00:48:04,266
Centering.

612
00:48:08,569 --> 00:48:09,849
Can you clean it up?

613
00:48:10,071 --> 00:48:11,511
I'm working on it.

614
00:48:24,509 --> 00:48:25,909
What the hell...?

615
00:48:26,679 --> 00:48:27,919
Try zooming out.

616
00:48:31,978 --> 00:48:32,898
Freeze!

617
00:48:33,105 --> 00:48:34,345
Reverse values.

618
00:48:36,026 --> 00:48:37,746
Try zooming out again.

619
00:48:41,826 --> 00:48:43,906
Rotate 90 degrees counterclock...

620
00:48:45,540 --> 00:48:47,060
My God!

621
00:48:53,844 --> 00:48:55,244
What's going on?

622
00:48:55,847 --> 00:48:58,127
You're not going to believe this.

623
00:49:11,662 --> 00:49:13,342
Does anybody speak German?

624
00:49:14,875 --> 00:49:17,155
"I declare the Games in Berlin...

625
00:49:18,338 --> 00:49:19,978
...at the celebration...

626
00:49:20,258 --> 00:49:23,018
...of the first Olympics
of the New Era...

627
00:49:23,346 --> 00:49:24,626
...as opened."

628
00:49:35,447 --> 00:49:36,847
Get me the White House.

629
00:49:37,700 --> 00:49:40,020
20 million people died
defeating the bastard...

630
00:49:40,329 --> 00:49:43,009
...and he's our first ambassador
to outer space?

631
00:49:43,334 --> 00:49:46,494
The broadcast of the '36 Olympics
was the first TV transmission...

632
00:49:46,880 --> 00:49:48,320
...that went into space.

633
00:49:48,591 --> 00:49:51,831
Sending it back is a way of saying,
"Hello, we heard you."

634
00:49:52,138 --> 00:49:54,338
Or, "Sieg Heil,
you're our kind of people."

635
00:49:54,642 --> 00:49:57,042
Hitler's politics
have nothing to do with this.

636
00:49:57,354 --> 00:50:00,874
It's unlikely they understood it.
People must understand...

637
00:50:01,193 --> 00:50:03,433
The people are
in very good hands, Doctor.

638
00:50:03,739 --> 00:50:05,419
We'll take it from here.

639
00:50:06,534 --> 00:50:08,454
Smile, folks. We're on.

640
00:50:08,829 --> 00:50:11,029
A message of unknown origin
from deep space...

641
00:50:11,333 --> 00:50:14,853
... was received by American
scientists. Now to the White House.

642
00:50:15,464 --> 00:50:18,544
We're told the President
will have only a few remarks...

643
00:50:18,969 --> 00:50:20,369
...about today's
extraordinary events...

644
00:50:20,638 --> 00:50:23,878
...and that he won't be taking
any questions from the press.

645
00:50:28,984 --> 00:50:30,224
Good afternoon.

646
00:50:33,157 --> 00:50:35,237
I'm glad to be joined by my...

647
00:50:35,494 --> 00:50:37,334
...Science and Technology Advisor.

648
00:50:39,166 --> 00:50:41,926
This is the product
of years of exploration...

649
00:50:42,212 --> 00:50:45,332
...by some of the world's
most distinguished scientists.

650
00:50:45,675 --> 00:50:47,275
Like all discoveries...

651
00:50:47,511 --> 00:50:49,751
...this one will continue
to be reviewed...

652
00:50:50,099 --> 00:50:51,099
...examined...

653
00:50:51,309 --> 00:50:52,789
...and scrutinized.

654
00:50:53,061 --> 00:50:55,941
It must be confirmed
by other scientists.

655
00:50:56,316 --> 00:50:57,436
But clearly...

656
00:50:58,069 --> 00:51:01,389
...the fact that this is being
explored is a vindication...

657
00:51:02,367 --> 00:51:06,047
Fish, what is the story over here?
I thought Ellie was supposed to be on.

658
00:51:06,373 --> 00:51:07,813
I don't know.

659
00:51:08,501 --> 00:51:09,781
Guys?

660
00:51:12,214 --> 00:51:14,774
Those interlaced frames
we thought were noise?

661
00:51:15,887 --> 00:51:18,447
This has structure.
I'm hearing structure.

662
00:51:19,892 --> 00:51:22,132
If this discovery is confirmed...

663
00:51:22,396 --> 00:51:25,916
...it will be one of the most stunning
insights into our universe...

664
00:51:26,235 --> 00:51:28,195
...that science has ever uncovered.

665
00:51:28,781 --> 00:51:31,061
Its implications
are as far-reaching...

666
00:51:31,368 --> 00:51:33,848
...and awe-inspiring
as can be imagined.

667
00:51:34,247 --> 00:51:37,487
Even as it promises answers
to some of our oldest questions...

668
00:51:37,877 --> 00:51:39,357
...it poses still others...

669
00:51:39,630 --> 00:51:41,190
...even more fundamental.

670
00:51:41,466 --> 00:51:43,306
We will continue
to listen closely...

671
00:51:43,594 --> 00:51:45,074
...to what it has to say...

672
00:51:45,305 --> 00:51:47,345
...as we continue
the search for answers...

673
00:51:47,642 --> 00:51:48,842
...and for knowledge...

674
00:51:49,144 --> 00:51:51,344
...that is as old
as humanity itself...

675
00:51:51,648 --> 00:51:54,448
...but essential
to our people's future.

676
00:51:54,986 --> 00:51:55,666
Thank you.

677
00:51:55,904 --> 00:51:58,664
Is there a renewed assessment
of security threat?

678
00:51:59,075 --> 00:52:01,995
I'll answer your questions
after a few corrections.

679
00:52:02,288 --> 00:52:03,928
The message was received Friday...

680
00:52:04,249 --> 00:52:06,209
...at 6:31 a.m.
Mountain Standard Time.

681
00:52:06,503 --> 00:52:08,063
It was largely mathematical...

682
00:52:08,297 --> 00:52:10,897
...and in spite of reports
to the contrary...

683
00:52:11,301 --> 00:52:13,701
...appears to be
completely benign in nature.

684
00:52:14,014 --> 00:52:17,814
Let me say that again.
The message is completely benign.

685
00:52:18,187 --> 00:52:21,187
The President has contacted
the world's heads of state...

686
00:52:21,525 --> 00:52:24,205
...and every security measure
is being taken.

687
00:52:24,529 --> 00:52:27,489
To better explain the events
of the last 48 hours...

688
00:52:27,826 --> 00:52:32,066
...is the leader of the scientific team
that made this remarkable discovery...

689
00:52:32,499 --> 00:52:36,339
...Dr. David Drumlin, special
Science Advisor to the President.

690
00:52:44,517 --> 00:52:45,837
Thank you, Rachel.

691
00:52:46,228 --> 00:52:47,308
Hello.

692
00:52:49,274 --> 00:52:51,594
In 1936,
a very faint television signal...

693
00:52:51,903 --> 00:52:56,023
...transmitted the opening ceremonies
of the Olympic Games as a show...

694
00:52:56,368 --> 00:52:58,768
...of German superior technology.

695
00:52:59,915 --> 00:53:03,875
That signal left Earth at the speed
of light and 26 years later...

696
00:53:04,296 --> 00:53:07,776
...arrived in the vicinity
of the star we call Vega.

697
00:53:09,095 --> 00:53:12,775
That signal has been sent back to us
hugely amplified...

698
00:53:13,309 --> 00:53:16,149
...an unmistakable
sign of intelligence.

699
00:53:16,439 --> 00:53:17,479
Kent, go ahead.

700
00:53:17,733 --> 00:53:21,893
The Adolf transmission used 25 frames
per second but we're receiving 50.

701
00:53:22,281 --> 00:53:25,961
So we put the other 25
through search algorithms.

702
00:53:26,329 --> 00:53:28,809
We found a series of markers
on the top of each frame.

703
00:53:29,124 --> 00:53:30,804
-Are you ready?
-Yeah, go ahead!

704
00:53:31,086 --> 00:53:32,246
Send it, Willie.

705
00:53:32,463 --> 00:53:33,903
Here it comes.

706
00:53:37,345 --> 00:53:38,545
It's digital...

707
00:53:38,805 --> 00:53:42,805
...massive amounts of data which
extend right to the higher harmonics.

708
00:53:43,646 --> 00:53:45,046
Jackpot!

709
00:53:46,358 --> 00:53:48,238
All right, as you'll see...

710
00:53:48,486 --> 00:53:51,766
...interlaced with the frames
of the original Hitler image...

711
00:53:52,117 --> 00:53:54,837
...we found these sections.

712
00:53:55,163 --> 00:53:58,483
We thought they were noise,
but they're actually data...

713
00:53:58,793 --> 00:54:00,073
...huge amounts of it.

714
00:54:00,337 --> 00:54:04,497
When we combine this with the data
from the original signal...

715
00:54:04,844 --> 00:54:08,004
...we get
these encrypted pages of text.

716
00:54:08,391 --> 00:54:12,351
No two are alike and
we've uncovered over 10,000 already.

717
00:54:12,689 --> 00:54:14,769
What does it mean, Doctor?

718
00:54:15,359 --> 00:54:17,999
We have no idea.
It could be anything.

719
00:54:18,364 --> 00:54:20,404
Volume 1 of an
Encyclopedia Galactica.

720
00:54:20,659 --> 00:54:23,219
Instructions for us
on their colonization procedures.

721
00:54:23,496 --> 00:54:25,736
Moses with a few billion
new commandments.

722
00:54:26,042 --> 00:54:28,082
How long will it take to decode it?

723
00:54:28,420 --> 00:54:31,580
It could take forever.
We really need a primer...

724
00:54:31,884 --> 00:54:34,884
We need to get
the best decryption people we have.

725
00:54:35,681 --> 00:54:39,721
I intend to use the VLA
as my command post.

726
00:54:40,062 --> 00:54:43,382
In the meantime, my office
has made out a preliminary budget.

727
00:54:43,693 --> 00:54:44,933
Wait a minute.

728
00:54:45,195 --> 00:54:47,435
This is a privately-funded
operation.

729
00:54:47,699 --> 00:54:49,899
We lease dish time
from the government...

730
00:54:50,202 --> 00:54:52,762
This is a clear-cut case of eminent
domain.

731
00:54:53,040 --> 00:54:56,080
I'm recommending to the President
we militarize this project.

732
00:54:56,461 --> 00:54:58,821
What?! This is my project!

733
00:54:59,090 --> 00:55:02,290
Nobody knows more about this
than I do. David, tell them...

734
00:55:02,595 --> 00:55:05,555
Excuse me!
Could we calm down here?

735
00:55:06,101 --> 00:55:07,301
I'm going to recommend that...

736
00:55:07,519 --> 00:55:10,439
...Dr. Drumlin coordinate
the decryption effort.

737
00:55:10,732 --> 00:55:13,932
But in light of Dr. Arroway's
long experience in these matters...

738
00:55:14,279 --> 00:55:18,279
...for the time being, she will
direct operations at the VLA...

739
00:55:18,619 --> 00:55:23,099
...understanding that future discoveries
will be kept in strict confidence...

740
00:55:23,501 --> 00:55:25,661
...until such time
as the President...

741
00:55:25,963 --> 00:55:29,643
...can decide the most suitable
course of action. Understood?

742
00:55:29,969 --> 00:55:30,929
Yes.

743
00:55:31,221 --> 00:55:33,421
This is CNN Breaking News.

744
00:55:34,058 --> 00:55:36,898
The President
called the message from Vega...

745
00:55:37,230 --> 00:55:39,310
... "a stunning insight
into our universe..."

746
00:55:44,657 --> 00:55:48,377
...as police clashed
with neo-Nazi protesters.

747
00:55:48,747 --> 00:55:50,787
So, there's life on other planets.

748
00:55:51,084 --> 00:55:54,524
Boy, this will really change
the Miss Universe contest.

749
00:55:55,340 --> 00:55:59,500
Health officials worldwide are concerned
that the message from Vega...

750
00:55:59,846 --> 00:56:02,406
...might trigger
a rash of mass suicides...

751
00:56:02,684 --> 00:56:05,204
...not unlike recent cult deaths
near San Diego...

752
00:56:05,563 --> 00:56:07,443
Even a scientist must admit...

753
00:56:07,691 --> 00:56:11,931
...there are some pretty serious
religious overtones to all this.

754
00:56:12,365 --> 00:56:14,525
Here's someone whose organization...

755
00:56:14,785 --> 00:56:17,145
...is accused of conducting
its own inquisition:

756
00:56:17,497 --> 00:56:20,137
Richard Rank,
head of the Conservative Coalition.

757
00:56:20,502 --> 00:56:21,502
Thank you.

758
00:56:21,712 --> 00:56:25,712
This is yet another example of science
intruding into matters of faith.

759
00:56:26,970 --> 00:56:30,130
This means they
have been reacting to TV signals...

760
00:56:30,517 --> 00:56:33,237
...from the 1930s.
They're just getting them.

761
00:56:33,605 --> 00:56:37,165
Imagine how disappointed
they'll be if they're Cubs fans.

762
00:56:37,610 --> 00:56:40,530
We now go to Jeremy Roth,
who is reporting...

763
00:56:40,824 --> 00:56:44,144
...from the Very Large Array
near Socorro, New Mexico.

764
00:56:44,537 --> 00:56:45,897
Like a bolt from the blue it came.

765
00:56:46,248 --> 00:56:48,128
"The Message from Vega"
has caused...

766
00:56:48,418 --> 00:56:50,698
...thousands of believers
